04060nam a22005895i 9780801461880DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014618807 a10.7591/97808014618802doi  a(DE-B1597)515270  a(OCoLC)1083582047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDU600b.T74 2008eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a996.112221 aTrnka, Susanna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aState of Suffering :bPolitical Violence and Community Survival in Fiji /cSusanna Trnka. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b1 map, 9 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Violence, Pain, and the Collapse of Everyday Life -- t2. The Coup of May 2000-An Invitation to Anti-Indian Violence -- t3. Living in Fantastic Times -- t4. Looting, Labor, and the Politics of Pain -- t5. Fear of a Nation Returning to ]ungli -- t6. Victims and Assailants, Victims and Friends -- t7. Restoring "Normalcy" in Postcoup Fiji -- tAcknowledgments -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do ordinary people respond when their lives are irrevocably altered by terror and violence? Susanna Trnka was residing in an Indo-Fijian village in the year 2000 during the Fijian nationalist coup. The overthrow of the elected multiethnic party led to six months of nationalist aggression, much of which was directed toward Indo-Fijians. In State of Suffering, Trnka shows how Indo-Fijians' lives were overturned as waves of turmoil and destruction swept across Fiji.Describing the myriad social processes through which violence is articulated and ascribed meaning-including expressions of incredulity, circulation of rumors, narratives, and exchanges of laughter and jokes-Trnka reveals the ways in which the community engages in these practices as individuals experience, and try to understand, the consequences of the coup. She then considers different kinds of pain caused by political chaos and social turbulence, including pain resulting from bodily harm, shared terror, and the distress precipitated by economic crisis and social dislocation.Throughout this book, Trnka focuses on the collective social process through which violence is embodied, articulated, and silenced by those it targets. Her sensitive ethnography is a valuable addition to the global conversation about the impact of political violence on community life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEast Indians -- Fiji. 0aEast IndianszFiji. 0aEthnic conflict -- Fiji. 0aEthnic conflictzFiji. 0aFiji -- Ethnic relations. 0aFiji -- Politics and government. 0aPolitical violence -- Fiji. 0aPolitical violencezFiji. 4aAnthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146188040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801461880423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801461880/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles